rustrations over unanswered petitions could provoke serious personal moments of crisis. In its detailed reconstruction of the mentalities of such unsuccessful and forgotten Royal 'assassins' as Margaret Nicholson, James Hadfield and Dennis Collins, this unique and pioneering study of monarchical history from below will interest the specialist and general reader alike, and provoke fresh controversy over the viability of monarchies in the modern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMonarchyzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aMonarchyzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aMonarchyzGreat BritainxPublic opinionxHistoryy18th century. 0aMonarchyzGreat BritainxPublic opinionxHistoryy19th century. 0aRegicideszGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aRegicideszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Modern / General.2bisacsh  aCrown.  aElizabeth II.  aFranklin L. Ford.  aGeorge III.  aMargaret Nicholson.  ahistoriographical approaches.  amonarchy.  amyth creation.  anarcissism.  apetitioning.  aplebeian English patriotism.  aroyal idleness.  aroyal space.  aterrorism.1 aPoole, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152613061740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526130617423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526130617/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles